## The Human Spine — Complete Guide

The spine (vertebral column) has **33 vertebrae** organized into 5 regions, shown from 3 angles in the diagram.

---

### 🟡 1. Cervical Vertebrae (C1–C7) — *Neck Region*

**7 vertebrae** — the topmost and most mobile section.

| Vertebra | Special Name | Function |
|----------|-------------|----------|
| C1 | **Atlas** | Supports the skull; allows nodding ("yes" motion) |
| C2 | **Axis** | Has a peg (dens) that Atlas rotates around; allows head rotation ("no" motion) |
| C3–C7 | — | Support neck movement and protect the spinal cord in the neck |

> C7 is the large bump you can feel at the base of your neck.

---

### 🟢 2. Thoracic Vertebrae (T1–T12) — *Mid-Back Region*

**12 vertebrae** — each one **attaches to a pair of ribs**, forming the rib cage.

- Protects the heart and lungs
- Less mobile than cervical vertebrae due to rib attachment
- Forms a natural **kyphotic curve** (slightly outward curve)
- T1 begins at the upper back; T12 is at the base of the rib cage

---

### 🟩 3. Lumbar Vertebrae (L1–L5) — *Lower Back Region*

**5 vertebrae** — the **largest and strongest** in the spine.

- Bear the majority of the body's weight
- Allow forward/backward bending and twisting
- Most common site of **back pain and disc herniation**
- L5 connects to the sacrum below
- Forms a natural **lordotic curve** (inward curve)

---

### 🦴 4. Sacrum (S1–S5) — *Pelvic Region*

**5 fused vertebrae** forming a single triangular bone.

- Connects the spine to the **hip bones (pelvis)**
- Forms the back wall of the pelvis
- Transfers body weight from the spine to the legs
- Fusion is complete by early adulthood

---

### 🦴 5. Coccyx — *Tailbone*

**3–5 fused vertebrae** at the very base of the spine.

- A vestigial remnant of a tail from our evolutionary ancestors
- Provides attachment point for muscles and ligaments of the pelvic floor
- Can be painful if fractured (usually from a fall)

---

### 📐 The Four Natural Curves (seen in Lateral View)

The right lateral view in the diagram clearly shows the S-shaped curvature:

| Region | Curve Type | Direction |
|--------|-----------|-----------|
| Cervical | Lordosis | Inward (forward) |
| Thoracic | Kyphosis | Outward (backward) |
| Lumbar | Lordosis | Inward (forward) |
| Sacral | Kyphosis | Outward (backward) |

These curves act like a **spring**, absorbing shock and maintaining balance during movement.

---

### ⚠️ Key Functions of the Spine
- **Protection** — encloses and shields the spinal cord
- **Support** — holds the body upright
- **Movement** — enables bending, twisting, and rotation
- **Shock absorption** — via intervertebral discs between each vertebra
- **Nerve pathway** — spinal nerves branch out at each vertebral level to control the entire body